this_week_changes.title: Baby brain boost
this_week_changes.description: Protect unborn brains! Women who get 400 micrograms of folic acid daily this early on reduce baby’s risk of neural tube defects by up to 70 percent.

this_week_changes.title: Chance of twins?
this_week_changes.description: Twin alert! If you’re over the age of 35 you produce lots of follicle-stimulating hormones and more follicles, upping the chance that two or more eggs will be released during ovulation.

this_week_changes.title: You're pregnant! Or are you?
this_week_changes.description: Surprise: You’re not actually pregnant during your first week of pregnancy! Your due date is calculated from the first day of your last period.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Baby brain boost
this_week_changes.description: Protect unborn brains! Women who get 400 micrograms of folic acid daily this early on reduce baby’s risk of neural tube defects by up to 70 percent.

this_week_changes.title: Chance of twins?
this_week_changes.description: Twin alert! If you’re over the age of 35 you produce lots of follicle-stimulating hormones and more follicles, upping the chance that two or more eggs will be released during ovulation.

this_week_changes.title: You're pregnant! Or are you?
this_week_changes.description: Surprise: You’re not actually pregnant during your first week of pregnancy! Your due date is calculated from the first day of your last period.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Baby on board!
this_week_changes.description: We have an embryo! Your soon-to-be fetus is still a cluster of cells that are growing and multiplying. It’s about the size of a pinhead.

this_week_changes.title: The journey begins
this_week_changes.description: It takes about four days for your fertilized egg — now dubbed a blastocyst — to reach your uterus and another two to three days to implant.

this_week_changes.title: Boy or girl?
this_week_changes.description: You probably won’t know if you’re having a baby boy or girl for about 14 more weeks, but sex is determined at the moment of fertilization.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Two sets of cells
this_week_changes.description: Your itty bitty embryo has two layers of cells called the epiblast and the hypoblast. Soon they’ll develop into all of your baby’s body parts and systems.

this_week_changes.title: Seeing double
this_week_changes.description: You normally don't have your first ultrasound until at least week 6, but you might be able to spot the gestational sac as early as halfway through week 4 — and if you're having twins, you'll likely see two of them!

this_week_changes.title: Baby's yolk sac
this_week_changes.description: Before the placenta forms, you develop a yolk sac, which can be visible next week. This sac produces blood and helps to nourish your young embryo.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: The placenta forms
this_week_changes.description: The placenta is under construction and will finish forming by the end of the first trimester. It’s an organ that will soon connect your developing fetus to your uterine wall, providing baby-to-be with nutrients and oxygen.

this_week_changes.title: Positive pregnancy test
this_week_changes.description: Your hCG hormone levels are now high enough to confirm you're having a baby in a home pregnancy test.

this_week_changes.title: From embryo to fetus
this_week_changes.description: That mass of cells we call an embryo is starting to look like a fetus, with a forming neural tube (pre-spinal cord and brain) running from head to rump.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Smile!
this_week_changes.description: Your little one’s face is taking shape this week, with cheeks, chin and jaws beginning to form.

this_week_changes.title: Baby's heart is gearing up!
this_week_changes.description: The cluster of cells that will become your baby's heart starts to pulse sometime after week 5. From week 6 of pregnancy or later, you may be able to see (and/or hear) cardiac activity for the first time on an ultrasound, though the exact timing of when it can be detected varies a little.

this_week_changes.title: Fetal position
this_week_changes.description: It’s not called the fetal position for nothing: Your baby-to-be, who looks like a tiny tadpole complete with teeny"tail," is curled up with the leg buds tucked in toward the torso. No plans to move soon!

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Baby's lifeline
this_week_changes.description: Umbilical cord, welcome to the womb! This tube joins baby and placenta, delivering oxygen and nutrients and even eliminating waste into your bloodstream.

this_week_changes.title: The mucus plug develops
this_week_changes.description: Your mucus plug debuts at the week’s close, settling into the opening of your cervix. This natural cork seals and protects your womb from bacteria.

this_week_changes.title: Webbed hands and feet
this_week_changes.description: Your baby-to-be has developed web-like hand and feet stubs. Soon enough, hands will grow and change to have fingers and toes, but right now, they look like little paddles.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Here's looking at you!
this_week_changes.description: Baby blue? Sea green? Coffee brown? You won’t see your baby’s eyes for a while, but this week the retinas have begun to form.

this_week_changes.title: Blue or pink?
this_week_changes.description: Your baby-to-be’s boy or girl parts are beginning to develop, but it’s still too soon for your doctor to detect which sex your baby will be.

this_week_changes.title: All systems go
this_week_changes.description: By the end of the week, all the essential organs and body systems have begun to develop.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Getting stronger
this_week_changes.description: This week, tiny muscles are starting to form, but it will be at least another month or two before you'll be able to feel those little punches.

this_week_changes.title: That sweet, sweet sound
this_week_changes.description: While it's too early to feel any kicks yet, it's not too early to hear something — fetal cardiac activity might be audible on a Doppler device at your doctor's appointment this week!

this_week_changes.title: Hi, baby
this_week_changes.description: The spinal cord "tail" at your baby-to-be's rump has all but disappeared! He's looking more and more like a tiny human.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Baby's first teeth
this_week_changes.description: While baby-to-be’s pearly whites won’t appear until she's about 6 months old, teeny tooth buds are now developing under the gums.

this_week_changes.title: Tummy time
this_week_changes.description: This week, the stomach is producing digestive juices and the kidneys are making larger quantities of urine.

this_week_changes.title: Building bones
this_week_changes.description: Bones and cartilage are forming this week, knees and ankles are starting to take shape and tiny elbows are already working!

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Can you hear me now?
this_week_changes.description: Your baby-to-be’s ears have migrated closer to their final destination on either side of his cute little head.

this_week_changes.title: Brainy baby
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s head accounts for about half of his body length. Wow!

this_week_changes.title: Little fingers and toes
this_week_changes.description: Bye-bye, webbed hands and feet. Your little one's fingers and toes are separating and looking like real baby parts. Fingernail and toenail beds are also beginning to develop.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: The big move
this_week_changes.description: During week 8, your baby’s intestines were infringing on umbilical cord space. But this week, they’re completing the move back into the abdomen.

this_week_changes.title: Future grandparent?
this_week_changes.description: Your baby's pituitary gland at the base of the brain has begun producing hormones, meaning your little one could give you grandchildren one day.

this_week_changes.title: Germ fighter
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s bone marrow is making white blood cells, so she’ll be able to fight off all those germs passed around the playground.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Eyes wide shut
this_week_changes.description: While baby’s eyes have arrived, they’re not open. His eyelids are fused shut to protect those tiny peepers as they continue to develop.

this_week_changes.title: The voice
this_week_changes.description: The promise of laughter, cries and very first words start now with the formation of vocal cords.

this_week_changes.title: Balancing out
this_week_changes.description: That big baby head is getting more in balance with the rest of the body. Right now, his head is about half the size of his total frame.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Say cheese!
this_week_changes.description: Are you making faces at me? To welcome your second trimester, your baby-to-be can now use facial muscles to grimace and smile.

this_week_changes.title: It's a boy (or girl)!
this_week_changes.description: Boy or girl? This week, fully developed genitals make their grand entrance. Note, however, that they still may be hard to detect on an ultrasound.

this_week_changes.title: Peach fuzz
this_week_changes.description: It's all about hair now as your baby's head, eyebrows and body start sprouting some fuzz.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: See-through baby
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s skin remains super thin, allowing developing blood vessels to show right through.

this_week_changes.title: Baby's got back
this_week_changes.description: Your little one’s skeleton is starting to ossify. Translation: If an X-ray were taken today, his skeleton would be visible.

this_week_changes.title: Falling into place
this_week_changes.description: Things are moving into place, namely your baby’s ears and eyes. They continue the slow migration to their rightful spots on baby’s face and head.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Sensitive to light
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s eyes are making small side-to-side movements this week and can perceive some light, even though they’re still closed.

this_week_changes.title: The sucking reflex
this_week_changes.description: That thumb-sucking habit of many newborns may have already begun. At 16 weeks, babies may be able to make sucking motions.

this_week_changes.title: Strong heart
this_week_changes.description: Baby-to-be’s circulatory system is now up and (beginning) to run. In fact, that little heart can pump about 25 quarts of blood a day.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Getting ready to feed
this_week_changes.description: Your little one is practicing sucking and swallowing as he gets ready for the real thing: a breast or bottle!

this_week_changes.title: Baby will soon be able to hear you!
this_week_changes.description: Baby's sense of hearing is making big strides this week. His ears are close to being fully formed and he's starting to be able to hear your voice.

this_week_changes.title: Warming up
this_week_changes.description: Fat stores are beginning to develop under your baby's skin. This provides energy and will help keep your little one warm (and cute) after birth.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Tiny fingerprints
this_week_changes.description: Your one-of-a-kind baby is truly one of a kind now, with unique fingerprints on those little fingertips and toes.

this_week_changes.title: Nerve protection
this_week_changes.description: Myelin, a protective insulation, is starting to form around baby-to-be's nerves. This covering continues to grow until your baby's first birthday.

this_week_changes.title: Girl and boy parts defined
this_week_changes.description: Having a girl? The fallopian tubes and uterus are now in proper position. A boy? Genitals may be visible on your next ultrasound.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Skin coating
this_week_changes.description: Your baby's sensitive skin is now covered in vernix caseosa, a greasy, white, cheese-like coating that protects his skin from being wrinkled at birth.

this_week_changes.title: Just breathe
this_week_changes.description: Your baby's lungs are developing, with the main airways (called bronchioles) beginning to form this week.

this_week_changes.title: Feel that kick?
this_week_changes.description: You may be able to feel baby move for the first time this week, but don't panic if you don't. You will soon!

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Your little ... thumbsucker?
this_week_changes.description: Your little one is still working hard on those sucking reflexes and may even use a thumb for practice.

this_week_changes.title: Gender reveal
this_week_changes.description: Boy or girl? Your ultrasound this week should be able to detect what you're having if you want to know!

this_week_changes.title: The big week?
this_week_changes.description: If you didn't start feeling your baby-to-be's punches and kicks last week, you may this week — and it's the best! But it could take a little longer.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: He's got the moves
this_week_changes.description: Your baby's arms and legs are in proportion this week and his movements are now much more coordinated. Also, notice a jump in baby's length this week? Up until now, we've been measuring from crown to rump, but now we start to measure from crown to heel, which explains why he suddenly "grew" so much.

this_week_changes.title: More blood cells
this_week_changes.description: Your baby-to-be's liver and spleen have been working hard producing blood cells, but now the bone marrow is developed enough to help too.

this_week_changes.title: Baby's drinking
this_week_changes.description: While the placenta is still #1 when it comes to nourishment, now your baby takes in small amounts of amniotic fluid, too.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: The flashlight test
this_week_changes.description: Though baby's eyelids are still sealed shut, your little one can perceive light and dark now. Shine a flashlight on your tummy and see if your cutie pie moves

this_week_changes.title: Watch what you say!
this_week_changes.description: Baby's ears are beginning to hear and process sounds from inside your body — your breathing, your rumbling tummy, your heartbeat.

this_week_changes.title: Learning to grab
this_week_changes.description: Baby's nervous system is sharpening the five senses, which means those little fingers are learning to grab those tiny ears, nose and umbilical cord.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Are you blushing?
this_week_changes.description: Baby's skin is a bit saggy (but won't be for long as fat begins forming) and has a pinkish-red hue (this is true in all skin colors), thanks to the developing veins and arteries right underneath.

this_week_changes.title: Packing a punch
this_week_changes.description: Those little arms and legs are packing more of a punch these days...you might even see them poke through from the outside!

this_week_changes.title: The power of the placenta
this_week_changes.description: The placenta — baby’s recently completed life-support system — transfers oxygen and nutrients to baby and removes waste products.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Bulking up
this_week_changes.description: Your little bean is putting on more and more weight, much of it coming from accumulating baby fat along with growing muscles, organs and bones.

this_week_changes.title: Rock-a-bye, baby
this_week_changes.description: Baby's auditory system is rapidly advancing, which means if she frequently hears a certain song now she's likely to recognize it and feel calmed by it when she's born.

this_week_changes.title: White-haired baby
this_week_changes.description: Your baby is still sporting white eyelashes, eyebrows and hair, all of which have yet to acquire pigment.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: The startle reflex
this_week_changes.description: Don’t scare the baby! Your little one’s startle reflexes are now developing. Hmm, perhaps you can scare baby’s hiccups away!

this_week_changes.title: Baby fat
this_week_changes.description: Baby fat is coming! Even though your baby-to-be is still lean, he's slowly putting on pounds and losing that wrinkly appearance.

this_week_changes.title: Hair debut?
this_week_changes.description: If your baby-in-waiting has hair, and not all do, the texture may actually be seen at this stage of the game.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Are you making eyes at me?
this_week_changes.description: Your little one is getting ready to woo you now that eyelashes are growing in. Soon you'll get to see your cutie bat those babies at you!

this_week_changes.title: Ouch!
this_week_changes.description: Teeny tiny fingernails have arrived! Be forewarned: They can be jagged and sharp by the time your baby arrives in your arms.

this_week_changes.title: Swallowing practice
this_week_changes.description: Your baby-to-be continues to work hard swallowing amniotic fluid this week. This act is instrumental to healthy lung development.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Ear muffs
this_week_changes.description: Your baby can hear you, but know that it’s muffled because the ears are still covered in vernix caseosa, that waxy protective coating on the skin.

this_week_changes.title: Baby's got hiccups
this_week_changes.description: If you’re feeling unusual movements in your belly, it may be hiccups. As baby’s lungs continue to develop, chances of hiccups increase.

this_week_changes.title: So active!
this_week_changes.description: Your little gymnast has started to develop muscle tone from all that kicking, rolling and punching he's doing.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Your little dreamer
this_week_changes.description: Your baby begins to experience REM (rapid eye movement) sleep, which means it’s very likely your little one is dreaming!

this_week_changes.title: Baby can blink
this_week_changes.description: So far, your baby’s eyes have been shut tight. Now, your little sweetie can open and close those beautiful eyes, complete with brand new fluttering eyelashes.

this_week_changes.title: Making faces
this_week_changes.description: Fetuses often stick out their tongues at this age. No one is sure exactly why, but it’s possible that your baby is tasting your amniotic fluid.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Baby's first smile
this_week_changes.description: Your baby may begin to smile this week, especially in his sleep.

this_week_changes.title: More hiccups
this_week_changes.description: Your little one is continuing to hiccup. They feel like light, rhythmic taps to you and aren’t uncomfortable for baby, either.

this_week_changes.title: Tight quarters
this_week_changes.description: As your little bean plumps up, your womb is getting a bit cramped, so those hard kicks you were feeling will be more like jabs and pokes now.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Wrinkly baby brain
this_week_changes.description: The surface of your baby’s brain begins to wrinkle — the wrinkles are called convolutions — so that it can hold more brain cells.

this_week_changes.title: Hold on tight!
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s hands are now fully formed and fingernails are growing. In ultrasounds, you may catch baby grabbing a foot.

this_week_changes.title: Do your kick counts!
this_week_changes.description: Your growing baby's quarters keep getting tighter, but you'll still feel movement every day. So don't forget those kick counts!

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Brain connections
this_week_changes.description: Your baby's brain connections are developing at a rapid pace, which is a good thing since he has to make billions of them!

this_week_changes.title: Sleepy baby
this_week_changes.description: Your baby is a drowsy one, putting in longer stretches of snooze time, specifically REM sleep. Want to wake him up? Eat or drink something sugary.

this_week_changes.title: Such a smarty
this_week_changes.description: Your brainy baby can already process information and pick up signals from all five senses.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Baby organs are fully formed
this_week_changes.description: All your baby’s major organs are fully developed now, except for the lungs. So even if you gave birth this week, your little one would probably do just fine.

this_week_changes.title: Breathing practice
this_week_changes.description: Your baby inhales amniotic fluid to practice using those lungs.

this_week_changes.title: Skin changes
this_week_changes.description: Bye-bye, see-through baby! This week, your little bean's skin is now opaque instead of transparent.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Soft spot
this_week_changes.description: The plates of bone in your baby’s skull are still fairly pliable, which makes it easier for him to squeeze down the birth canal.

this_week_changes.title: Thirsty baby
this_week_changes.description: Your baby drinks up to a pint of amniotic fluid a day! This helps prepare your baby’s gastrointestinal system for prime time.

this_week_changes.title: Packing on the pounds
this_week_changes.description: Your baby is gaining weight at a fast clip now, putting on about half a pound a week. He'll come close to doubling his weight by the time he's born.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Sleep schedule
this_week_changes.description: Your baby closes those cute eyes when she snoozes and opens them when she’s awake, helping your little one settle into a sleep schedule.

this_week_changes.title: Thick skin
this_week_changes.description: The waxy, cheesy coating on your baby’s skin — vernix — begins to thicken this week before it starts shedding in the next few weeks.

this_week_changes.title: Poking through
this_week_changes.description: As your baby grows, you may be able to see body parts like little hands and feet through your belly!

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Snug as a bug
this_week_changes.description: With less space in your uterus now, your baby’s movements have shifted from kicks and punches to rolls and wiggles.

this_week_changes.title: Padding up
this_week_changes.description: The majority of your baby’s growth now is fat. His shoulders in particular are padding up for the journey south.

this_week_changes.title: Head down
this_week_changes.description: By this week, almost all babies are positioned with their heads facing down toward your cervix, ready for their trip out.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: So cute!
this_week_changes.description: Your baby looks more like an infant this week, with chubby little legs and pink-tinted skin — even in babies of color because of the blood vessels just beneath the surface.

this_week_changes.title: Bionic hearing
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s ears are extra sharp during these last few weeks. Studies show she may even recognize your voice and favorite songs after birth.

this_week_changes.title: Baby may drop
this_week_changes.description: If this is your first birth, your baby may drop lower into your pelvis this week in what is called “lightening” or “dropping.”

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Dress rehearsal
this_week_changes.description: If your baby were born this week, he’d still be early term but will be full-term by week 39. He’s practicing for his grand entrance by inhaling and exhaling amniotic fluid, blinking and turning from side to side.

this_week_changes.title: Hang on!
this_week_changes.description: Your baby has developed more dexterity in his fingers. He can now grasp onto smaller objects, like a toe or his nose.

this_week_changes.title: More thumbsucking
this_week_changes.description: Your baby is likely sucking his thumb a lot these days in preparation for his feeding sessions after birth.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: I see you!
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s eyes right now are blue, gray or brown, but once they’re exposed to light, they may change color or shade. By the time your baby turns 1, you’ll know their true color.

this_week_changes.title: Shedding hair
this_week_changes.description: The lanugo, the fine downy hair that covered your little one's body for warmth, is falling off in preparation for delivery.

this_week_changes.title: Ready to cry
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s lungs have strengthened and the vocal cords have developed, which means she’s ready to communicate through wails and cries.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Big baby brain
this_week_changes.description: While your baby’s body isn’t growing as much, his brain is. It’s already 30 percent bigger than it was just four weeks ago.

this_week_changes.title: Pink skin turns white
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s pinkish skin has turned whitish or whitish-grayish and won’t have pigment, no matter what his eventual skin color will be, until shortly after birth.

this_week_changes.title: Baby's at his birth weight!
this_week_changes.description: Your baby has likely reached his birth weight of somewhere between 6 and 9 pounds, about a third of which is accounted for by his head.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Dry skin alert
this_week_changes.description: Since your baby has already shed most of her vernix, the waxy coating that acted as a moisturizer, some dry spots may appear on the skin.

this_week_changes.title: Past your due date?
this_week_changes.description: If baby hasn't arrived this week, you're in good company: An estimated 30 percent of pregnancies proceed past the 40-week mark.

this_week_changes.title: Talk to baby
this_week_changes.description: Be sure that you and your partner talk to your little bundle a lot after baby makes her grand entrance. She'll likely recognize the sound of your voices!

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Baby manicure
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s nails will definitely need a manicure and pedicure with a pair of baby nail clippers or nail file after birth. By now, they’ve grown well past his fingertips.

this_week_changes.title: You're not overdue yet!
this_week_changes.description: Don’t worry, your baby is not considered overdue until 42 weeks gestation. Fewer than 5 percent of babies arrive on their due date.

this_week_changes.title: Heart check
this_week_changes.description: Your baby’s heartbeat will likely be monitored this week through nonstress tests. His heart rate should quicken each time he moves.

title: Your baby is as big as a poppy seed.

this_week_changes.title: Helping labor along
this_week_changes.description: To induce labor, your doctor may use a drug called Pitocin, which is safe for you and baby and helps start contractions.

this_week_changes.title: Time to be induced?
this_week_changes.description: Since there's a chance your placenta may not provide as much oxygen and nutrients to your baby, your doctor might recommend inducing labor to be safe.

this_week_changes.title: Checking up on baby
this_week_changes.description: Though most babies continue to thrive well past week 40, your doctor will continue to monitor baby with a biophysical profile: an ultrasound to assess the baby, plus a nonstress test.
